The genre of the original "teenage kicks" song by the undertones can quite easily be identified as punk rock, most notably by its instantly aggressive and almost violent tone. It starts immediately with distorted guitars and a punchy drum beat, leaving little room for dynamic progression. This starkly contrasts the cover by nouvelle vague, which starts with only a single classical guitar playing a signature bossa nova rhythm with 7th chords, as opposed to the original 5th chords signature to punk. Light percussive taps and shakers begin in the second half of the intro in place of a drum kit, and the vocals start normally in the verse with the overall sound being notably cleaner than the original. 
As the original song comes into its chorus's, the texture of the song stays mostly the same. The only difference from the verses being an extra set of vocals acting as backup harmonies, whereas the cover version adds another shaker and a distorted lead guitar playing the original riff in a much more stripped down form. The distorted guitar is unexpected and uncharacteristic of the bossa style, however it manages to stay unobtrusive to the songs style by staying simple and refraining from taking center stage as distorted guitars often do. 
For the instrumental after the second chorus, the original song simply removes the vocals, yet nouvelle vague's version also removes most of the percussion to bring a greater sense of dynamics to the piece. 
In terms of structure, the two compositions remain the same for the first 2 chorus's, until after the instrumental where the cover version simply sticks to playing variations of the chorus until the end whereas the original continues with the verse/chorus structure as normal.
